 an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\")\n   2. [A.2 Loss Bound Analysis](#A1.SS2 \"In Appendix A Theoretical Analysis ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\")\n      1. [Lower Bound of Positive Weighted Loss](#A1.SS2.SSS0.Px1 \"In A.2 Loss Bound Analysis ‣ Appendix A Theoretical Analysis ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\")\n10. [B Limitations and Future Work](#A2 \"In RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\")\n11. [C Case Study](#A3 \"In RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\")\n \n\n[License: CC BY 4.0](https://info.arxiv.org/help/license/index.html#licenses-available) \n\narXiv:2502.11026v3 [cs.LG] 21 Mar 2026\n\n# RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\n\nYuhao Du yuhaodu@link.cuhk.edu.cn   \nShenzhen Research Institute of Big Data   \nThe Chinese University of Hong Kong, Shenzhen Zhuo Li11footnotemark: 1 zhuoli3@link.cuhk.edu.cn   \nShenzhen Research Institute of Big Data   \nThe Chinese University of Hong Kong, Shenzhen Pengyu Cheng11footnotemark: 1 pengyucheng95@gmail.com   \nQwen LLM Application Team, Alibaba Zhihong Chen zhihongc@stanford.edu   \nStanford University Yuejiao Xie yuejiaoxie@link.cuhk.edu.cn   \nThe Chinese University of Hong Kong, Shenzhen Xiang Wan wanxiang@sribd.cn   \nShenzhen Research Institute of Big Data Anningzhe Gao anningzhegao@gmail.com   \nShenzhen Research Institute of Big Data  Equal Contribution.Corresponding Author. Code is available at <https://github.com/DuYooho/VAR>.\n\n###### Abstract\n\nReinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) is crucial for aligning Large Language Models (LLMs) with human values. However, RLHF has been continuously challenged by its high complexity in implementation and computation consumption, specifically for online sampling-based methods like Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) and Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO). Even with recent simplifications, such as Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) that designs an offline implicit reward learning objective relying on pre-collected preference datasets, the problems of over-fitting and training instability remain hindering the alignment process from the expected optimal performance. To address the existing challenges, we propose a novel simplification of RLHF from the perspective of variational inference, called Variational Alignment with Re-weighting (VAR). Specifically, by directly minimizing the distribution gap between the learning LLM policy and the optimal solution of RLHF, we transform the alignment objective into an offline reward-driven re-weighted supervised fine-tuning (SFT) form, which only requires minor adjustment on the SFT loss to obtain noticeable improvement on training stability and effectiveness. In comprehensive evaluation benchmarks, our objective empowers LLMs to outperform offline alignments, demonstrating superior performance in both helpfulness and harmlessness metrics (avg. ↑7.16%\\uparrow 7.16\\% than DPO). Meanwhile, when compared to online sampling methods, our method is also comparable even better while significantly reducing computational overhead and accelerating convergence speed (over 5×5\\times faster than GRPO), suggesting our approach as an efficient and effective solution in bridging the gap between efficiency and performance in LLM alignment.\n\n## 1 Introduction\n\nLarge Language Models (LLMs) (OpenAI, [2024](#bib.bib5 \"GPT-4 technical report\"); Touvron et al., [2023a](#bib.bib4 \"LLaMA: open and efficient foundation language models\"); Yang et al., [2024](#bib.bib22 \"Qwen2. 5 technical report\")) have achieved remarkable success in extensive applications of artificial intelligence (AI), including dialogue generation (Abdullin et al., [2024](#bib.bib58 \"Synthetic dialogue dataset generation using llm agents\")), summarization (Hu et al., [2022](#bib.bib83 \"Graph enhanced contrastive learning for radiology findings summarization\")), coding (Cobbe et al., [2021](#bib.bib20 \"Training verifiers to solve math word problems\"); Shao et al., [2024](#bib.bib28 \"DeepSeekMath: pushing the limits of mathematical reasoning in open language models\")), logical reasoning (Suzgun et al., [2022](#bib.bib60 \"Challenging big-bench tasks and whether chain-of-thought can solve them\")), AI agents (Wu et al., [2023](#bib.bib59 \"Autogen: enabling next-gen llm applications via multi-agent conversation framework\"); Hu et al., [2025a](#bib.bib74 \"Beyond emotion recognition: a multi-turn multimodal emotion understanding and reasoning benchmark\"); [b](#bib.bib75 \"AgentMental: an interactive multi-agent framework for explainable and adaptive mental health assessment\"); Dai et al., [2025](#bib.bib85 \"Psyche-r1: towards reliable psychological llms through unified empathy, expertise, and reasoning\")), and data curation (Du et al., [2025](#bib.bib76 \"Atoxia: red-teaming large language models with target toxic answers\"); Li et al., [2024a](#bib.bib78 \"Self-instructed derived prompt generation meets in-context learning: unlocking new potential of black-box llms\"); [2025b](#bib.bib79 \"Add-one-in: incremental sample selection for large language models via a choice-based greedy paradigm\")). Among the diverse LLM training techniques, Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) plays a core role in ensuring the LLM generation is helpful and harmless (Ouyang et al., [2022](#bib.bib7 \"Training language models to follow instructions with human feedback\"); Rafailov et al., [2024](#bib.bib23 \"Direct preference optimization: your language model is secretly a reward model\")).\n\nIn particular, RLHF first learns a reward model (RM) (Bradley and Terry, [1952](#bib.bib57 \"Rank analysis of incomplete block designs: i. the method of paired comparisons\")) from annotated human preferences, then trains LLMs within a reinforcement learning (RL) scheme via Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) (Schulman et al., [2017](#bib.bib27 \"Proximal policy optimization algorithms\")) to optimize the expected rewards from the learned RM (Ouyang et al., [2022](#bib.bib7 \"Training language models to follow instructions with human feedback\")). Although recognized as the mainstream solution to LLM alignment (Ouyang et al., [2022](#bib.bib7 \"Training language models to follow instructions with human feedback\"); Shao et al., [2024](#bib.bib28 \"DeepSeekMath: pushing the limits of mathematical reasoning in open language models\"); Touvron et al., [2023b](#bib.bib40 \"Llama 2: open foundation and fine-tuned chat models\"); OpenAI, [2024](#bib.bib5 \"GPT-4 technical report\"); Yang et al., [2024](#bib.bib22 \"Qwen2. 5 technical report\")), RLHF remains being challenged because of its expensive computational resource consumption (Cheng et al., [2023](#bib.bib61 \"Adversarial preference optimization\"); Yuan et al., [2023](#bib.bib62 \"Rrhf: rank responses to align language models with human feedback without tears\")) and complicated implementation (Ouyang et al., [2022](#bib.bib7 \"Training language models to follow instructions with human feedback\"); Shao et al., [2024](#bib.bib28 \"DeepSeekMath: pushing the limits of mathematical reasoning in open language models\"); Yuan et al., [2023](#bib.bib62 \"Rrhf: rank responses to align language models with human feedback without tears\")) in which multiple models (e.g. the learning policy, the reference, the critic model, and the reward model) are required to cooperate in the online RL training scheme. Moreover, incorporating such a complicated pipeline significantly induces training complexity and instability, leading to the difficulty of training convergence and the high risk of collapse (Song et al., [2023](#bib.bib63 \"Reward collapse in aligning large language models\"); Go et al., [2023](#bib.bib64 \"Aligning language models with preferences through f-divergence minimization\")). Although methods like GRPO (Shao et al., [2024](#bib.bib28 \"DeepSeekMath: pushing the limits of mathematical reasoning in open language models\")) forego the critic model, instead estimating the baseline from group scores and significantly reducing training resources, its online sampling strategy still challenges the practical implementation and training speed.\n\nTowards more stable training than online alignment, several ranking-based offline alternatives are proposed, primarily from the perspective of enlarging the likelihood margin between preferred and rejected response pairs in a contrastive approach. Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) (Rafailov et al., [2024](#bib.bib23 \"Direct preference optimization: your language model is secretly a reward model\")) implicitly maximizes the difference in sampling probabilities between good and bad answers. Ethayarajh et al. (Ethayarajh et al., [2024](#bib.bib31 \"Kto: model alignment as prospect theoretic optimization\")) introduces Kahneman-Tversky Optimization (KTO) to directly maximize the utility of generations instead of maximizing the log-likelihood of preferences. While effective, these methods usually rely on the collection of preferred / rejected response pairs with high quality, which introduces a substitution data collection consumption. Instead, Advantage Leftover Launch (A-LoL) (Baheti et al., [2024](#bib.bib13 \"Leftover lunch: advantage-based offline reinforcement learning for language models\")) formulates the RL process at the sequence level and derives an advantage-based offline objective that exclusively utilizes preferred responses to achieve human-aligned results. However, it still relies on clipping the importance weights to ensure training stability, which prevents the optimization from reaching the true RLHF optima. Furthermore, approaches like DPO and ALoL could employ negative weights for potential dis-preferred responses, leading to an unstable training process due to the unbounded nature of loss landscape when negative weights are applied (Pal et al., [2024](#bib.bib55 \"Smaug: fixing failure modes of preference optimisation with dpo-positive\"); Yan et al., [2024](#bib.bib56 \"3D-properties: identifying challenges in dpo and charting a path forward\")).\n\nIn this paper, we address these limitations by proposing a reward-driven variational offline alignment framework that eliminates the need for online sampling and clipping, and avoids the instability introduced by negative weights. Our approach reformulates RLHF as a variational inference problem over positive measures, ensuring a stable and well-defined optimization landscape. Specifically, starting from the closed-form optimal solution of RLHF, we directly minimize the Kullback–Leibler (KL) divergence (Kullback and Leibler, [1951](#bib.bib65 \"On information and sufficiency\")) between the to-be-learned LLM and its optimal solution. The resulting loss function takes the form of an offline reward-driven weighted supervised fine-tuning (SFT) loss, where non-negative weights are derived through an exponential reward transformation. Furthermore, we introduce an efficient in-batch normalization technique to approximate the normalization term, enabling scalable and practical implementation. Experimental results demonstrate that our framework outperforms existing methods in both stability and alignment performance, providing a robust alternative to the challenges of RLHF.\n\n## 2 Preliminary\n\n#### Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback\n\nis an essential approach to alignment LLMs with human values, especially from the perspectives of helpfulness and harmlessness (Ouyang et al., [2022](#bib.bib7 \"Training language models to follow instructions with human feedback\")). We denote the input query to LLMs as 𝒙∈𝒳{\\bm{x}}\\in{\\mathcal{X}}, and the model response 𝒚∈𝒴{\\bm{y}}\\in{\\mathcal{Y}}, where 𝒳,𝒴{\\mathcal{X}},{\\mathcal{Y}} are discrete enumerable sample spaces containing natural language sequences. RLHF first learns a reward model r​(𝒙,𝒚)r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}) from a given collection of human preference data 𝒟p={(𝒙,𝒚w,𝒚l)}\\mathcal{D}\\_{\\text{p}}=\\{({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}\\_{w},{\\bm{y}}\\_{l})\\}, where 𝒙{\\bm{x}} is a user input prompt, 𝒚w,𝒚l{\\bm{y}}\\_{w},{\\bm{y}}\\_{l} are the preferred and rejected responses selected by annotators, respectively. To learn a representative RM, following Bradley-Terry (Bradley and Terry, [1952](#bib.bib57 \"Rank analysis of incomplete block designs: i. the method of paired comparisons\")) objective is usually utilized:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| −𝔼(𝒙,𝒚w,𝒚l)∼𝒟p​[log⁡σ​(r​(𝒙,𝒚w)−r​(𝒙,𝒚l))],-\\mathbb{E}\\_{({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}\\_{w},{\\bm{y}}\\_{l})\\sim{\\mathcal{D}}\\_{\\text{p}}}\\Big[\\log\\sigma(r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}\\_{w})-r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}\\_{l}))\\Big], | (1) |\n\nwhere σ​(⋅)\\sigma(\\cdot) is the Sigmoid function. Intuitively, Equation [1](#S2.E1 \"In Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback ‣ 2 Preliminary ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") induces r​(𝒙,𝒚)r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}) to assign a higher reward score to the preferred response 𝒚w{\\bm{y}}\\_{w} than the rejected response 𝒚l{\\bm{y}}\\_{l} with respect to input 𝒙{\\bm{x}}.\n\nWith a learned RM r​(𝒙,𝒚)r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}), RLHF optimizes the target LLM policy πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}) by maximizing the expected reward:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝔼𝒙∼𝒟,𝒚∼πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)​[r​(𝒙,𝒚)]−β​KL​[πθ∥πref],\\mathbb{E}\\_{{\\bm{x}}\\sim\\mathcal{D},{\\bm{y}}\\sim\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}[r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}})]-\\beta\\text{KL}[\\pi\\_{\\theta}\\|\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}], | (2) |\n\nwhere KL​[πθ∥πref]\\text{KL}[\\pi\\_{\\theta}\\|\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}] is the KL divergence (Kullback and Leibler, [1951](#bib.bib65 \"On information and sufficiency\")) between the training policy πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}) with a reference model πref​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}) to prevent πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}) from the degeneration and preserve the generation diversity. β>0\\beta>0 is a hyper-parameter to re-weight the expected reward and the KL regularization term.\n\nTo solve the RLHF objective in Equation [2](#S2.E2 \"In Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback ‣ 2 Preliminary ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"), Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) (Schulman et al., [2017](#bib.bib27 \"Proximal policy optimization algorithms\")) has been recognized as the mainstream optimization algorithm (Rafailov et al., [2024](#bib.bib23 \"Direct preference optimization: your language model is secretly a reward model\")). However, as mentioned in Section [1](#S1 \"1 Introduction ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"), PPO suffers from training instability and high complexity in computation and implementation (Yuan et al., [2023](#bib.bib62 \"Rrhf: rank responses to align language models with human feedback without tears\"); Cheng et al., [2023](#bib.bib61 \"Adversarial preference optimization\")). Therefore, many of recent works have been proposed to simplify and improve the original PPO algorithm. Rafailov et al. (Rafailov et al., [2024](#bib.bib23 \"Direct preference optimization: your language model is secretly a reward model\")) theoretically demonstrate that Equation [2](#S2.E2 \"In Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback ‣ 2 Preliminary ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") has a closed-form solution:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| π∗​(𝒚|𝒙)=1Z​(𝒙)​πref​(𝒚|𝒙)​exp⁡(1β​r​(𝒙,𝒚)),\\pi^{\\*}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})=\\frac{1}{Z({\\bm{x}})}\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})\\exp\\left(\\frac{1}{\\beta}r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}})\\right), | (3) |\n\nwhere Z​(𝒙)=𝔼𝒚∼πref​(𝒚|𝒙)​[exp​(1β​r​(𝒙,𝒚))]Z({\\bm{x}})=\\mathbb{E}\\_{{\\bm{y}}\\sim\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}[\\text{exp}(\\frac{1}{\\beta}r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}))] is the denominator that normalizes the conditional distribution. Based on the relation between the optimal policy π∗​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi^{\\*}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}) and the RM r​(𝒙,𝒚)r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}), Rafailov et al. (Rafailov et al., [2024](#bib.bib23 \"Direct preference optimization: your language model is secretly a reward model\")) convert the RM learning objective Equation [1](#S2.E1 \"In Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback ‣ 2 Preliminary ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") to an optimal policy learning loss named Direct Preference Optimization (DPO):\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| −𝔼𝒟p​[log⁡σ​(β​log⁡πθ​(𝒚w|𝒙)πref​(𝒚w|𝒙)−β​log⁡πθ​(𝒚l|𝒙)πref​(𝒚l|𝒙))].-\\mathbb{E}\\_{{\\mathcal{D}}\\_{\\text{p}}}\\Big[\\log\\sigma\\Big(\\beta\\log\\frac{\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}\\_{w}|{\\bm{x}})}{\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}\\_{w}|{\\bm{x}})}-\\beta\\log\\frac{\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}\\_{l}|{\\bm{x}})}{\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}\\_{l}|{\\bm{x}})}\\Big)\\Big]. | (4) |\n\nBaheti et al. (Baheti et al., [2024](#bib.bib13 \"Leftover lunch: advantage-based offline reinforcement learning for language models\")) adopt the PPO objective into an offline scheme by using importance sampling and converting the expectation of πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}) to the expectation of πref​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}), then propose Advantage-Leftover-Lunch (A-LoL) gradient estimation:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| −𝔼𝒙∼𝒟,𝒚∼πref​(𝒚|𝒙)​[A^πref⋅πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)πref​(𝒚|𝒙)⋅∇θlog⁡πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)],-{\\mathbb{E}}\\_{{\\bm{x}}\\sim{\\mathcal{D}},{\\bm{y}}\\sim\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}\\Big[\\hat{A}^{\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}}\\cdot\\frac{\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}{\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}\\cdot\\nabla\\_{\\theta}\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})\\Big], | (5) |\n\nwhere A^πref\\hat{A}^{\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}} is the estimated advantage value (Schulman et al., [2016](#bib.bib3 \"High-dimensional continuous control using generalized advantage estimation\")) with respect to πθ¯\\pi\\_{\\bar{\\theta}}, also calculated offline.\n\n#### Variational Methods\n\nprovide a principled framework for approximating unknown probability distributions by leveraging optimization over a family of tractable parameterized distributions (Kingma and Welling, [2022](#bib.bib66 \"Auto-encoding variational bayes\")). The fundamental idea of variational methods is to reformulate probabilistic inference as a functional optimization problem. More specifically, in the domain of machine learning, the goal is to find a surrogate distribution qθ​(𝒚)q\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}) from a parameterized family 𝒬={qθ|θ∈Θ}\\mathcal{Q}=\\{q\\_{\\theta}|\\theta\\in\\Theta\\}, so that qθ​(𝒚)q\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}) can best approximates the target unknown distribution p​(𝒚)p({\\bm{y}}). For example, in variational inference (Blei et al., [2017](#bib.bib67 \"Variational inference: a review for statisticians\")), the unknown distribution p​(𝒚)p({\\bm{y}}) is approximated by minimizing the inverse KL divergence between qθ​(𝒚)q\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}) and p​(𝒚)p({\\bm{y}}):\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| minqθ∈𝒬⁡KL​[qθ​(𝒚)∥p​(𝒚)]=minθ∈Θ⁡𝔼𝒚∼qθ​(𝒚)​[log⁡qθ​(𝒚)p​(𝒚)].\\min\\_{q\\_{\\theta}\\in{\\mathcal{Q}}}\\text{KL}[q\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}})\\|p({\\bm{y}})]=\\min\\_{\\theta\\in\\Theta}\\mathbb{E}\\_{{\\bm{y}}\\sim q\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}})}[\\log\\frac{q\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}})}{p({\\bm{y}})}]. | (6) |\n\nVariational inference has been widely applied in various models such as variational autoencoders (VAEs) (Doersch, [2016](#bib.bib68 \"Tutorial on variational autoencoders\")), Bayesian Neural Networks (BNNs) (Graves, [2011](#bib.bib69 \"Practical variational inference for neural networks\")), and Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) (Blei et al., [2003](#bib.bib70 \"Latent dirichlet allocation\")). Besides, the forward KL divergence KL​[p∥qθ]=𝔼𝒚∼p​(𝒚)​[log⁡p​(𝒚)qθ​(𝒚)]\\text{KL}[p\\|q\\_{\\theta}]=\\mathbb{E}\\_{{\\bm{y}}\\sim p({\\bm{y}})}[\\log\\frac{p({\\bm{y}})}{q\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}})}] has also been recognized as an effective objective for variational methods, and has been applied in multiple machine learning scenarios such as f-divergence optimization (Namkoong and Duchi, [2016](#bib.bib71 \"Stochastic gradient methods for distributionally robust optimization with f-divergences\")), reinforcement learning (Schulman et al., [2017](#bib.bib27 \"Proximal policy optimization algorithms\")), and Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) (Salimans et al., [2015](#bib.bib72 \"Markov chain monte carlo and variational inference: bridging the gap\")).\n\n## 3 Methodology\n\n### 3.1 Variational LLM Alignment\n\nWe consider the RLHF task from a novel perspective of variational methods. Instead of optimizing the learning policy πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}) using the objective in Equation [2](#S2.E2 \"In Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback ‣ 2 Preliminary ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"), we can minimize the forward KL​[π∗∥πθ]\\text{KL}[\\pi^{\\*}\\|\\pi\\_{\\theta}] between the optimal policy π∗​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi^{\\*}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}) and the learning policy πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}):\n\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| KL​[π∗∥πθ]\\displaystyle\\text{KL}[\\pi^{\\*}\\|\\pi\\_{\\theta}] | =𝔼π∗​[log⁡π∗​(𝒚|𝒙)πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)]=−H​(π∗)−𝔼π∗​[log⁡πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)],\\displaystyle=\\mathbb{E}\\_{\\pi^{\\*}}\\bigg[\\log\\frac{\\pi^{\\*}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}{\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}\\bigg]=-H(\\pi^{\\*})-\\mathbb{E}\\_{\\pi^{\\*}}[\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})], | (7) |\n\nwhere H​(⋅)H(\\cdot) is the entropy of π∗\\pi^{\\*} and is a constant with respect to the model parameters θ\\theta. For conciseness, we adopt the expectation form of the KL divergence and let 𝔼π\\mathbb{E}\\_{\\pi} denote 𝔼y∼π​(𝒚|𝒙)\\mathbb{E}\\_{y\\sim\\pi({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}. As a result, the approximation of π∗\\pi^{\\*} under minimizing KL divergence can be achieved by:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| minθ⁡KL​[π∗∥πθ]=maxθ⁡𝔼π∗​[log⁡πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)].\\min\\_{\\theta}\\text{KL}[\\pi^{\\*}\\|\\pi\\_{\\theta}]=\\max\\_{\\theta}\\mathbb{E}\\_{\\pi^{\\*}}[\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})]. | (8) |\n\nUsing importance sampling (Goertzel, [1950](#bib.bib52 \"Quota sampling and importance functions in stochastic solution of particle problems\"); Kahn and Harris, [1951](#bib.bib53 \"Estimation of particle transmission by random sampling\"); Kloek and Van Dijk, [1978](#bib.bib51 \"Bayesian estimates of equation system parameters: an application of integration by monte carlo\")), which effectively approximates an unknown distribution with a known one, we can rearrange Equation [8](#S3.E8 \"In 3.1 Variational LLM Alignment ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") to obtain the following objective by incorporating the closed-form solution of π∗\\pi^{\\*} in Equation [3](#S2.E3 \"In Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback ‣ 2 Preliminary ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"):\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| 𝔼π∗[logπθ(𝒚|𝒙)]=𝔼πref[π∗​(𝒚|𝒙)πref​(𝒚|𝒙)logπθ(𝒚|𝒙)]=𝔼πref[exp⁡(1β​r​(𝒙,𝒚))Z​(𝒙)⏟Reward-driven Weight⋅log⁡πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)⏟Log-likelihood]=:ℒVAR.\\mathbb{E}\\_{\\pi^{\\*}}[\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})]=\\mathbb{E}\\_{\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}}\\bigg[\\frac{\\pi^{\\*}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}{\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})\\bigg]={\\mathbb{E}}\\_{\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}}\\bigg[\\underbrace{\\frac{\\exp(\\frac{1}{\\beta}r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}))}{Z({\\bm{x}})}}\\_{\\text{Reward-driven Weight}}\\cdot\\underbrace{\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}\\_{\\text{Log-likelihood}}\\bigg]=:{\\mathcal{L}}\\_{\\text{VAR}}. |\n\nThis overall objective contains two parts: a reward-driven weight and the log-likelihood of πθ\\pi\\_{\\theta} on the samples from the reference πref\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}, which reform the loss as a re-weight SFT loss. We call this novel alignment objective as Variational Alignment with Re-weighting (VAR). However, Z​(𝒙)=𝔼𝒚∼πref​(𝒚|𝒙)​[exp​(1β​r​(𝒙,𝒚))]Z({\\bm{x}})=\\mathbb{E}\\_{{\\bm{y}}\\sim\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})}[\\text{exp}(\\frac{1}{\\beta}r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}))] as the partition function remains unknown. Therefore, in the following subsection, we discuss the estimation of Z​(𝒙)Z({\\bm{x}}) within each training micro-batch.\n\n### 3.2 Batch-wise Partition Estimation\n\nEquation [3.1](#S3.Ex1 \"3.1 Variational LLM Alignment ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") implies that the key challenge in effectively approximating π∗\\pi^{\\*} through a parameterized model πθ\\pi\\_{\\theta} lies in the computation of Z​(𝒙)Z({\\bm{x}}). However, estimating Z​(𝒙)Z({\\bm{x}}) involves summing over all possible outputs yy for a given xx, which can be computationally expensive, as mentioned in previous work (Rafailov et al., [2024](#bib.bib23 \"Direct preference optimization: your language model is secretly a reward model\")). To avoid directly computing Z​(𝒙)Z({\\bm{x}}), some alignment methods adopt policy gradient algorithms (e.g., REINFORCE (Williams, [1992](#bib.bib54 \"Simple statistical gradient-following algorithms for connectionist reinforcement learning\")) and PPO (Schulman et al., [2017](#bib.bib27 \"Proximal policy optimization algorithms\"))) that optimize πθ\\pi\\_{\\theta} without explicitly normalizing over all outputs. Hence, with a batch of sample pairs ℬ={𝒙i,𝒚i}i=1B,𝒚i∼πref(⋅|𝒙i)\\mathcal{B}=\\{{\\bm{x}}\\_{i},{\\bm{y}}\\_{i}\\}\\_{i=1}^{B},{\\bm{y}}\\_{i}\\sim\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}(\\cdot|{\\bm{x}}\\_{i}), we approximate each Z​(𝒙i)Z({\\bm{x}}\\_{i}) using Monte Carlo estimation (Salimans et al., [2015](#bib.bib72 \"Markov chain monte carlo and variational inference: bridging the gap\")):\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Z​(𝒙i)\\displaystyle Z({\\bm{x}}\\_{i}) | =𝔼𝒚∼πref​(𝒚|𝒙i)​[exp​(1β​r​(𝒙i,𝒚))]=∑𝒚∈𝒴exp​(1β​r​(𝒙i,𝒚))⋅πref​(𝒚|𝒙i)\\displaystyle={\\mathbb{E}}\\_{{\\bm{y}}\\sim\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}\\_{i})}[\\text{exp}(\\frac{1}{\\beta}r({\\bm{x}}\\_{i},{\\bm{y}}))]=\\sum\\_{{\\bm{y}}\\in{\\mathcal{Y}}}\\text{exp}(\\frac{1}{\\beta}r({\\bm{x}}\\_{i},{\\bm{y}}))\\cdot\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}\\_{i}) |\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| ≈1B∑j=1Bexp(1βr(𝒙i,𝒚j))⋅πref(𝒚j|𝒙i)=:Z^(𝒙i).\\displaystyle\\approx\\frac{1}{B}\\sum\\_{j=1}^{B}\\text{exp}(\\frac{1}{\\beta}r({\\bm{x}}\\_{i},{\\bm{y}}\\_{j}))\\cdot\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}\\_{j}|{\\bm{x}}\\_{i})=:\\hat{Z}({\\bm{x}}\\_{i}). | (9) |\n\nWhen the batch size BB is large enough, we can collect diverse 𝒚j∼πref(⋅|𝒙i){\\bm{y}}\\_{j}\\sim\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}(\\cdot|{\\bm{x}}\\_{i}) and assume that {𝒚j}j=1B\\{{\\bm{y}}\\_{j}\\}\\_{j=1}^{B} are uniformly distributed in sample space 𝒴{\\mathcal{Y}}. With the above estimation, we can calculate the objective in equation [3.1](#S3.Ex1 \"3.1 Variational LLM Alignment ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") with a batch ℒ^VAR​(ℬ)=\\hat{{\\mathcal{L}}}\\_{\\text{VAR}}({\\mathcal{B}})=\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 1B​∑i=1B[exp⁡(1β​r​(𝒙i,𝒚i))Z^​(𝒙i)⋅log⁡πθ​(𝒚i|𝒙i)].\\frac{1}{B}\\sum\\_{i=1}^{B}\\bigg[\\frac{\\exp(\\frac{1}{\\beta}r({\\bm{x}}\\_{i},{\\bm{y}}\\_{i}))}{\\hat{Z}({\\bm{x}}\\_{i})}\\cdot\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}\\_{i}|{\\bm{x}}\\_{i})\\bigg]. | (10) |\n\nIn conclusion, we summarize the algorithm process of our in-batch estimation and loss computation in Algorithm [1](#algorithm1 \"In 3.2 Batch-wise Partition Estimation ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\").\n\nInput : Batch ℬ={(𝒙i,𝒚i)}i=1B\\mathcal{B}=\\{({\\bm{x}}\\_{i},{\\bm{y}}\\_{i})\\}\\_{i=1}^{B}, policy πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}), reference πref​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}), reward model r​(𝒙,𝒚)r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}).\n\nfor *i←1i\\leftarrow 1 to BB* do\n\nCompute policy logit log⁡πθ​(𝒚i|𝒙i)\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}\\_{i}|{\\bm{x}}\\_{i}) for the given input–output pair.\n\nEvaluate reference logits {πref​(𝒚j|𝒙i)}j=1B\\{\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}\\_{j}|{\\bm{x}}\\_{i})\\}\\_{j=1}^{B} over all candidates in the batch.\n\nObtain rewards {r​(𝒙i,𝒚j)}j=1B\\{r({\\bm{x}}\\_{i},{\\bm{y}}\\_{j})\\}\\_{j=1}^{B} for each candidate given 𝒙i{\\bm{x}}\\_{i}.\n\nCalculate Z^​(𝒙i)=1B​∑j=1Bexp⁡(1β​r​(𝒙i,𝒚j))⋅πref​(𝒚j|𝒙i)\\hat{Z}({\\bm{x}}\\_{i})=\\frac{1}{B}\\sum\\_{j=1}^{B}\\exp(\\frac{1}{\\beta}r({\\bm{x}}\\_{i},{\\bm{y}}\\_{j}))\\cdot\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}\\_{j}|{\\bm{x}}\\_{i}) as the reward-weighted normalization term.\n\nCompute ℒ^i=1Z^​(𝒙i)​exp⁡(1β​r​(𝒙i,𝒚i))⋅log⁡πθ​(𝒚i|𝒙i)\\hat{{\\mathcal{L}}}\\_{i}=\\frac{1}{\\hat{Z}({\\bm{x}}\\_{i})}\\exp(\\frac{1}{\\beta}r({\\bm{x}}\\_{i},{\\bm{y}}\\_{i}))\\cdot\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}\\_{i}|{\\bm{x}}\\_{i}) as the per-sample loss term for the ii-th example.\n\nend for\n\nUpdate πθ\\pi\\_{\\theta} with L^VAR​(ℬ)=1B​∑i=1Bℒ^i\\hat{L}\\_{\\text{VAR}}({\\mathcal{B}})=\\frac{1}{B}\\sum\\_{i=1}^{B}\\hat{{\\mathcal{L}}}\\_{i} via gradient descent.\n\nAlgorithm 1 VAR training within a batch\n\n### 3.3 Comparison with Previous Methods\n\nExisting preference alignment methods exhibit two fundamental limitations. First, clipping-based approaches like PPO (Schulman et al., [2017](#bib.bib27 \"Proximal policy optimization algorithms\")):\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝔼𝒙∼𝒟,𝒐∼πold​(𝒐|𝒙)​1|𝒐|​∑t=1|𝒐|min⁡[πθ​(𝒐t|𝒙,o<t)πold​(𝒐t|𝒙,o<t)​At,clip⁡(πθ​(𝒐t|𝒙,o<t)πold​(𝒐t|𝒙,o<t),1−ϵ,1+ϵ)​At],\\mathbb{E}\\_{{\\bm{x}}\\sim\\mathcal{D},{\\bm{o}}\\sim\\pi\\_{\\text{old}}({\\bm{o}}|{\\bm{x}})}\\frac{1}{|{\\bm{o}}|}\\sum\\_{t=1}^{|{\\bm{o}}|}\\min\\left[\\frac{\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{o}}\\_{t}|{\\bm{x}},o\\_{ | (11) |\n\nand A-LoL (Baheti et al., [2024](#bib.bib13 \"Leftover lunch: advantage-based offline reinforcement learning for language models\")) (ref to equation [5](#S2.E5 \"In Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback ‣ 2 Preliminary ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\")) bound the importance ratio πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)/πref​(𝒚|𝒙)\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})/\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}) within the interval [1−ϵ,1+ϵ][1-\\epsilon,1+\\epsilon]. This flattens the reward distinctions between responses with similar values. For instance, when two responses have rewards R1=100R\\_{1}=100 and R2=99R\\_{2}=99, clipped methods assign nearly identical probabilities (∼1/2\\sim 1/2), failing to resolve fine-grained preferences (detailed analysis in Appendix [A.1](#A1.SS1 \"A.1 Analysis of Clip Operator and Policy Distinction ‣ Appendix A Theoretical Analysis ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\")).\n\nSecond, existing methods such as DPO and A-LoL may encounter optimization instabilities caused by imbalanced or incorrect gradient dynamics. In particular, the gradient descent on dis-preferred responses can become pathologically strong, leading to an unstable optimization landscape. Consider the general weighted SFT objective:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| ℒW-SFT=−𝔼​[w​(𝒙,𝒚)​log⁡πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)].\\mathcal{L}\\_{\\text{W-SFT}}=-\\mathbb{E}\\bigg[w({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}})\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})\\bigg]. | (12) |\n\nWhen w​(𝒙,𝒚)w({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}}) takes negative values for dis-preferred responses, the loss becomes unbounded below. Minimizing the loss corresponds to maximizing w​(𝒙,𝒚)​log⁡πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)w({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}})\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}). For negative weights (w<0w<0), this reduces to minimizing log⁡πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}}), creating a non-compact optimization landscape. While perfect performance (log⁡πθ​(𝒚|𝒙)→0\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})\\rightarrow 0) is theoretically achievable, it is practically unreachable (Gao et al., [2023](#bib.bib49 \"Scaling laws for reward model overoptimization\")) (detailed analysis in Appendix [A.2](#A1.SS2 \"A.2 Loss Bound Analysis ‣ Appendix A Theoretical Analysis ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\")).\n\nOur key insight is that reward-driven alignment should operate in the space of positive measures. We therefore propose a variational method that naturally induces non-negative weights through exponential reward transformation:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| w​(𝒙,𝒚)∝πref​(𝒚|𝒙)​exp⁡(r​(𝒙,𝒚)/β)>0.w({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}})\\propto\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}}({\\bm{y}}|{\\bm{x}})\\exp(r({\\bm{x}},{\\bm{y}})/\\beta)>0. | (13) |\n\nThis construction guarantees that the loss landscape has well-defined minima bounded by the reference policy’s support. By reformulating RLHF as variational inference over positive measures, we achieve stable optimization without artificial clipping or negative weighting.\n\n## 4 Experiments\n\nTo evaluate the effectiveness of our proposed approach, we conducted experiments under two primary settings: (1) the Helpful and Harmless Assistant Task (HHA) (Bai et al., [2022](#bib.bib15 \"Training a helpful and harmless assistant with reinforcement learning from human feedback\"); Ganguli et al., [2022](#bib.bib16 \"Red teaming language models to reduce harms: methods, scaling behaviors, and lessons learned\")); and (2) generative benchmarks, including MMLU (Hendrycks et al., [2020](#bib.bib17 \"Measuring massive multitask language understanding\")), HumanEval (Chen et al., [2021](#bib.bib18 \"Evaluating large language models trained on code\")), BigBench-Hard (Srivastava et al., [2023](#bib.bib19 \"Beyond the imitation game: quantifying and extrapolating the capabilities of language models\")), and GSM8k (Cobbe et al., [2021](#bib.bib20 \"Training verifiers to solve math word problems\")).\n\n### 4.1 HHA Settings\n\n#### Dataset\n\nOur primary experiment utilizes the HHA dataset, which consists of user-assistant conversations paired with model-generated responses labeled as “chosen” or “rejected” based on human preferences. This dataset is divided into four subsets: (1) Harmless-base, containing red-teaming conversations designed to elicit harmful responses; (2) Helpful-base, (3) Helpful-online, and (4) Helpful-rejection, which focus on advice- and assistance-seeking interactions. We evaluate our method using the test sets of these subsets, comprising a total of 8.2K test conversations annotated with human preference labels.\n\nFor model training, we employ the OffsetBias (Park et al., [2024](#bib.bib14 \"OffsetBias: leveraging debiased data for tuning evaluators\")) dataset, a preference dataset similar to HHA. We utilize OffsetBias because our method explicitly relies on reward scores during training. We observed that directly applying the HHA training set and its corresponding reward models often results in inappropriate reward scores, such as instances where the chosen response receives a lower reward score than the rejected response. This issue significantly compromises the effectiveness of our method. In contrast, OffsetBias addresses six common types of biases, including length bias—where models tend to assign higher scores to longer sequences—that can mislead reward models into assigning inaccurate reward scores. By mitigating these biases, OffsetBias provides more robust and reliable reward scores, making it better suited for training our model effectively. For all HHA experiments, we use the full training set of OffsetBias, which consists of 8.5K samples.\n\n#### Models\n\nTo evaluate the scalability of our method, we conducted experiments on two model collections: Llama-{1B, 3B, 8B, 13B}111To ensure the use of the most updated models, we selected Llama3.2-{1B, 3B}, Llama3.1-8B, and Llama2-13B. (Dubey et al., [2024](#bib.bib21 \"The llama 3 herd of models\")) and Qwen2.5-{0.5B, 1.5B, 3B, 7B, 14B, 32B} (Yang et al., [2024](#bib.bib22 \"Qwen2. 5 technical report\")). Specifically, we benchmark our method against DPO across all models and consider two RL training settings: 1) starting from the pre-trained (base) model; (2) starting from the SFT model. For the reward model, we employ a popular OffsetBiasRM (Park et al., [2024](#bib.bib14 \"OffsetBias: leveraging debiased data for tuning evaluators\")) that is trained on the OffsetBias preference dataset. OffsetBiasRM is designed to provide more accurate reward scores by addressing common biases, making it more suitable for our experiments.\n\n \n\nTable 1: Reward scores obtained by aligning Llama model series using the OffsetBias training set and evaluating on the four subsets of the HHA benchmark. Additionally, we report the test reward on the split test set of OffsetBias. “Avg. Helpful” denotes the average reward across Helpful-base, Helpful-online, and Helpful-rejection, while “Avg. All” represents the average reward across all four subsets of HHA.\n\n| Method | Harmless ↑\\uparrow | Helpful ↑\\uparrow | Avg. Helpful ↑\\uparrow | Avg. All ↑\\uparrow | OffsetBias ↑\\uparrow |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| base | base | online | rejection |\n| Llama3.2-1B | Base | 37.03 | 20.51 | 24.04 | 21.93 | 22.16±1.34 | 25.88±1.59 | 21.00 |\n| DPO | 45.50 | 44.45 | 47.07 | 45.61 | 45.71±0.16 | 45.66±0.08 | 37.31 |\n| VAR | 52.48 | 57.35 | 60.58 | 59.38 | 59.10±0.24 | 57.44±0.14 | 56.81 |\n| SFT+DPO | 56.43 | 64.65 | 64.95 | 65.90 | 65.16±0.43 | 62.98±0.30 | 59.09 |\n| SFT+VAR | 60.19 | 65.96 | 68.94 | 68.27 | 67.72±0.11 | 65.84±0.07 | 61.97 |\n| Llama3.2-3B | Base | 35.05 | 26.50 | 31.15 | 28.60 | 28.75±0.38 | 30.33±0.14 | 26.61 |\n| DPO | 53.71 | 59.38 | 60.04 | 60.55 | 59.99±0.05 | 58.42±0.09 | 53.94 |\n| VAR | 57.97 | 60.23 | 64.92 | 62.92 | 62.69±0.04 | 61.51±0.08 | 60.88 |\n| SFT+DPO | 64.00 | 69.44 | 71.01 | 71.56 | 70.67±0.08 | 69.00±0.05 | 63.81 |\n| SFT+VAR | 64.00 | 67.93 | 71.32 | 70.83 | 70.02±0.22 | 68.52±0.12 | 63.72 |\n| Llama3.1-8B | Base | 38.73 | 34.74 | 39.96 | 37.30 | 37.33±0.65 | 37.68±0.46 | 30.42 |\n| DPO | 56.17 | 59.89 | 61.02 | 60.86 | 60.59±0.02 | 59.48±0.03 | 51.38 |\n| VAR | 57.18 | 61.13 | 65.57 | 64.33 | 63.68±0.20 | 62.06±0.11 | 63.91 |\n| SFT+DPO | 62.38 | 69.16 | 70.00 | 70.61 | 69.93±0.07 | 68.04±0.11 | 60.88 |\n| SFT+VAR | 63.24 | 68.13 | 71.13 | 70.78 | 70.01±0.47 | 68.32±0.51 | 65.75 |\n| Llama2-13B | Base | 33.06 | 27.39 | 29.53 | 28.36 | 28.43±0.04 | 29.59±0.13 | 27.05 |\n| DPO | 50.52 | 50.01 | 53.68 | 52.24 | 51.98±0.15 | 51.61±0.14 | 51.75 |\n| VAR | 58.45 | 58.94 | 62.94 | 61.89 | 61.26±0.24 | 60.56±0.25 | 61.44 |\n| SFT+DPO | 55.19 | 59.90 | 60.61 | 61.26 | 60.59±0.25 | 59.24±0.19 | 59.09 |\n| SFT+VAR | 61.29 | 63.27 | 66.07 | 65.75 | 65.03±0.15 | 64.09±0.09 | 62.59 |\n\n#### Evaluation\n\nBy following previous work (Rafailov et al., [2024](#bib.bib23 \"Direct preference optimization: your language model is secretly a reward model\"); Baheti et al., [2024](#bib.bib13 \"Leftover lunch: advantage-based offline reinforcement learning for language models\")), we adopt two popular evaluation strategies: 1) Reward Score: A higher reward score usually indicates more useful and helpful response with respective to the input. Specifically, we use the OffsetBiasRM reward model (Park et al., [2024](#bib.bib14 \"OffsetBias: leveraging debiased data for tuning evaluators\")) to calculate reward scores for sequences generated by the aligned models on the HHA test set. Additionally, we also evaluate reward scores on the split OffsetBias evaluation set to assess the in-distribution ability of the models. 2) Pairwise Winrate Score: Following the common practice of LLM-as-a-judge, we evaluate model outputs from the HHA test set using the GPT-4 judge with its standardized prompt template from MT-Bench (Zheng et al., [2023](#bib.bib9 \"Judging llm-as-a-judge with mt-bench and chatbot arena\"))222Note that we only adopt the MT-Bench judging protocol but do not use the MT-Bench benchmark itself.. To alleviate potential positional bias, we present the responses of two models to the judge in two different orders and compare their scores. A model is considered to win only if it does not lose in both orderings. Specifically, we define: Wins: Outperforms in both orderings or wins in one and ties in the other. Tie: Ties in both orderings or wins in one and loses in the other. Loses: Lags in both orderings or ties in one and loses in the other.\n\n#### Implementation Details\n\nFor all comparisons, we ensure consistent settings between our method and DPO. We select learning rates of 1e-5 and 5e-6, employing the AdamW optimizer with a cosine learning rate scheduler. For the Winrate evaluation, we randomly sample 99 instances from each of the four subsets of the HHA test set and conduct experiments using three different random seeds to compute the mean and standard error. To mitigate potential positional bias in GPT-4’s preferences, we randomly shuffle the positions of model-generated sequences and the SFT target during evaluation using gpt-4o-2024-11-20. For the Reward evaluation, we use the entire HHA test set, evaluating across three different random seeds to compute the mean and standard error. We employ generation parameters τ=0.8\\tau=0.8, top\\_p=0.9\\text{top\\\\_p}=0.9 and top\\_k=50\\text{top\\\\_k}=50 for all the generations. All models are trained on 4×\\timesA100-80GB GPUs, with Llama3-8B and Qwen2.5-14B utilizing 8×\\timesA100-80GB. Due to resource constraints, Qwen2.5-32B is trained using 4-bit quantization (bnb-4bit)333<https://huggingface.co/docs/bitsandbytes> across 4 nodes, each with 8×\\timesA100-80GB GPUs.\n\n \n\nTable 2: Reward scores obtained by aligning Qwen2.5 model series using the OffsetBias training set and evaluating on the four subsets of the HHA benchmark. Additionally, we report the test reward on the split test set of OffsetBias. “Avg. Helpful” denotes the average reward across Helpful-base, Helpful-online, and Helpful-rejection, while “Avg. All” represents the average reward across all four subsets of HHA.\n\n| Method | Harmless ↑\\uparrow | Helpful ↑\\uparrow | Avg. Helpful ↑\\uparrow | Avg. All ↑\\uparrow | OffsetBias ↑\\uparrow |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| base | base | online | rejection |\n| Qwen2.5-0.5B | Base | 33.03 | 25.44 | 30.86 | 26.94 | 27.75±0.30 | 29.06±0.14 | 40.38 |\n| DPO | 55.21 | 55.50 | 56.24 | 56.75 | 56.17±0.53 | 55.93±0.45 | 53.44 |\n| VAR | 55.22 | 58.09 | 62.32 | 60.38 | 60.26±0.21 | 59.00±0.07 | 59.50 |\n| SFT+DPO | 56.42 | 58.02 | 60.38 | 59.91 | 59.44±0.03 | 58.68±0.02 | 55.88 |\n| SFT+VAR | 58.22 | 61.72 | 63.58 | 63.56 | 62.95±0.14 | 61.77±0.12 | 60.63 |\n| Qwen2.5-1.5B | Base | 35.01 | 26.18 | 32.11 | 28.13 | 28.81±0.12 | 30.36±0.32 | 26.52 |\n| DPO | 53.40 | 57.00 | 57.38 | 57.85 | 57.41±0.17 | 56.41±0.13 | 56.63 |\n| VAR | 61.33 | 64.72 | 68.87 | 68.01 | 67.20±0.09 | 65.73±0.05 | 64.75 |\n| SFT+DPO | 54.51 | 61.13 | 61.54 | 62.26 | 61.64±0.32 | 59.86±0.28 | 57.63 |\n| SFT+VAR | 62.76 | 66.07 | 69.13 | 68.78 | 67.99±0.13 | 66.69±0.03 | 65.88 |\n| Qwen2.5-3B | Base | 47.07 | 34.27 | 41.86 | 36.61 | 37.58±0.14 | 39.96±0.18 | 45.06 |\n| DPO | 60.58 | 63.37 | 63.84 | 64.90 | 64.03±0.53 | 63.17±0.51 | 58.97 |\n| VAR | 63.30 | 66.29 | 70.07 | 69.32 | 68.56±0.08 | 67.24±0.05 | 66.06 |\n| SFT+DPO | 54.61 | 58.45 | 58.69 | 60.19 | 59.11±0.17 | 57.98±0.17 | 52.63 |\n| SFT+VAR | 65.15 | 67.86 | 71.24 | 70.78 | 69.96±0.06 | 68.75±0.05 | 65.63 |\n| Qwen2.5-7B | Base | 42.49 | 42.02 | 47.96 | 44.21 | 44.73±0.53 | 44.17±0.28 | 54.09 |\n| DPO | 61.51 | 66.09 | 66.50 | 67.28 | 66.62±0.18 | 65.35±0.10 | 65.81 |\n| VAR | 64.86 | 66.41 | 70.87 | 69.78 | 69.02±0.09 | 67.98±0.03 | 65.38 |\n| SFT+DPO | 60.78 | 62.02 | 61.62 | 62.67 | 62.10±0.25 | 61.77±0.30 | 56.91 |\n| SFT+VAR | 64.96 | 66.46 | 69.81 | 69.39 | 68.55±0.11 | 67.65±0.05 | 65.38 |\n| Qwen2.5-14B | Base | 39.29 | 32.73 | 39.03 | 35.16 | 35.64±0.08 | 36.55±0.27 | 45.16 |\n| DPO | 55.83 | 55.63 | 59.04 | 57.61 | 57.43±0.32 | 57.03±0.26 | 62.94 |\n| VAR | 64.24 | 65.23 | 69.79 | 68.50 | 67.84±0.14 | 66.94±0.03 | 65.63 |\n| SFT+DPO | 66.97 | 67.83 | 68.16 | 68.94 | 68.31±0.42 | 67.97±0.38 | 67.94 |\n| SFT+VAR | 66.37 | 67.74 | 71.70 | 71.08 | 70.17±0.21 | 69.22±0.10 | 66.44 |\n| Qwen2.5-32B-Int4 | Base | 38.80 | 34.36 | 39.13 | 36.78 | 36.77 | 37.27 | 38.97 |\n| DPO | 37.09 | 31.38 | 34.58 | 33.04 | 33.00 | 34.02 | 32.38 |\n| VAR | 50.03 | 45.36 | 51.77 | 47.77 | 48.30 | 48.73 | 57.69 |\n| SFT+DPO | 37.95 | 27.70 | 28.63 | 28.16 | 28.16 | 30.61 | 30.23 |\n| SFT+VAR | 53.18 | 49.07 | 55.66 | 51.90 | 52.21 | 52.45 | 59.09 |\n\n### 4.2 HHA Results\n\n#### Reward Evaluation\n\nTable [1](#S4.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ Models ‣ 4.1 HHA Settings ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") present the reward scores on the HHA test sets. DPO and VAR denote models trained directly from the Base model (pre-trained only), while SFT+ refers to models first fine-tuned via SFT and then further fine-tuned on the SFT model. From Table [1](#S4.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ Models ‣ 4.1 HHA Settings ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"), we observe that our method outperforms DPO in both Avg. Helpful and Avg. All across all Llama models for the base version, as well as for the SFT+ version, except for Llama3.2-3B, where it shows a marginal decrease of around 0.5% compared to DPO. Additionally, our method achieves comparable results whether trained directly from the base model or the SFT model, particularly for larger LLMs such as Llama3.1-8B and Llama2-13B, whereas DPO struggles to achieve strong results when starting from the base model. Moreover, our method achieves performance comparable to the RLHF objective in a single training step, resembling the simplicity and efficiency of SFT. Table [2](#S4.T2 \"Table 2 ‣ Implementation Details ‣ 4.1 HHA Settings ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") further demonstrates the scalability of our method across different model sizes. Our approach consistently outperforms DPO across all average reward scores on both HHA and OffsetBias, even when starting from the base model. For Qwen2.5-32B, due to limited resources, we employ 4-bit quantization for training. Nevertheless, our method maintains its advantage over DPO.\n\n![Refer to caption](2502.11026v3/figures/aligned_model_v_sft_target-llama-v2.png)\n\n![Refer to caption](2502.11026v3/figures/aligned_model_v_sft_target-qwen-v2.png)\n\nFigure 1: GPT-4 evaluation results on the HHA test set for the Llama (top) and Qwen (bottom) series, reporting average win rates, where error bars are calculated across three different random seeds.\n\n   \n\nTable 3: Winrate results for the Llama3 series instruct versions (1B, 3B, and 8B) on the HHA benchmark.\n\n| Method | Harmless-base ↑\\uparrow | Helpful-base ↑\\uparrow | Helpful-online ↑\\uparrow | Helpful-rejection ↑\\uparrow | Avg. Winrate ↑\\uparrow |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| A win | B win | Tie | A win | B win | Tie | A win | B win | Tie | A win | B win | Tie | All | Helpful |\n| Llama3.2-1B | DPO | 20.2 | 59.6 | 20.2 | 49.49 | 32.32 | 18.18 | 12.46 | 71.38 | 16.16 | 34.68 | 47.47 | 17.84 | 29.21±0.17 | 32.21±0.41 |\n| VAR | 55.56 | 34.34 | 10.10 | 72.73 | 16.50 | 10.77 | 48.48 | 42.42 | 9.09 | 69.36 | 19.86 | 10.77 | 61.53±0.22 | 63.53±0.30 |\n| Llama3.2-3B | DPO | 76.10 | 20.54 | 3.37 | 76.77 | 14.81 | 8.42 | 49.83 | 44.10 | 6.06 | 62.97 | 25.59 | 11.45 | 66.42±0.58 | 63.19±0.74 |\n| VAR | 63.30 | 26.26 | 10.44 | 89.90 | 3.70 | 6.40 | 61.96 | 32.66 | 5.39 | 79.13 | 12.12 | 8.75 | 73.57±0.95 | 76.99±0.98 |\n| Llama3.1-8B | DPO | 42.42 | 42.42 | 15.15 | 68.69 | 19.19 | 12.12 | 33.33 | 54.21 | 12.46 | 53.20 | 31.65 | 15.15 | 49.41±0.17 | 51.74±0.11 |\n| VAR | 51.52 | 33.67 | 14.81 | 88.55 | 8.08 | 3.37 | 58.59 | 34.34 | 7.07 | 85.86 | 10.44 | 3.70 | 71.13±0.34 | 77.67±0.30 |\n\n#### Winrate Evaluation\n\nFigure [1](#S4.F1 \"Figure 1 ‣ Reward Evaluation ‣ 4.2 HHA Results ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") presents the win rates evaluated by GPT-4o for answers generated by aligned models compared to the SFT targets (chosen answers in the test set) for the Llama and Qwen series. The Llama series show results consistent with the reward scores, where our method outperforms DPO across all models except Llama2-13B, which achieves comparable results. For the Qwen series, our method outperforms DPO across all Qwen models except Qwen2.5-14B, where it shows a slight decrease. The Qwen series exhibit slightly different trends compared to the reward scores, with our method starting from the base version outperforming the SFT+ version across scales from 0.5B to 14B and achieving comparable results at 32B. These findings further demonstrate that our method can achieve the RLHF objective in a single SFT-like step without the need for resource-intensive reinforcement learning.\n\nTable [3](#S4.T3 \"Table 3 ‣ Reward Evaluation ‣ 4.2 HHA Results ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") shows results on the Llama series instruct versions (i.e., models after RLHF). Our method outperforms DPO by a large margin across three scales (1B, 3B, and 8B) and consistently achieves higher win rates across all subsets of the HHA benchmark. This demonstrates the robustness of our method across models at different training stages, including those that have already undergone RLHF alignment. The results highlight the effectiveness of our approach in further refining and aligning models with human preferences, even when starting from pre-aligned instruct versions.\n\n![Refer to caption](2502.11026v3/figures/llama3.2_1b_val_reward.png) \n\n(a) Llama3.2-1B\n\n![Refer to caption](2502.11026v3/figures/llama3.2_3b_val_reward.png) \n\n(b) Llama3.2-3B\n\n![Refer to caption](2502.11026v3/figures/llama3.1_8b_val_reward.png) \n\n(c) Llama3.1-8B\n\nFigure 2: Average validation reward during the training process for (a) Llama3.2-1B, (b) Llama3.2-3B, and (c) Llama3.1-8B on the OffsetBias dataset, comparing DPO and our method.\n\n#### Training Stability\n\nFigure [2](#S4.F2 \"Figure 2 ‣ Winrate Evaluation ‣ 4.2 HHA Results ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") illustrates the average validation reward during the training process for three Llama model collections. Comparing our method with DPO, we observe that DPO exhibits greater volatility and tends to decline from the early training steps. In contrast, our method demonstrates a gradual increase in validation reward, ultimately reaching a consistent level. This indicates that our approach is more robust over longer training steps and maintains a more stable training process compared to DPO.\n\n#### Comparison with Online Methods\n\n \n\nTable 4: Comparison between offline VAR and online GRPO methods on Qwen2.5-3B and Llama3.2-3B, including training time per epoch.\n\n| Method | Harmless ↑\\uparrow | Helpful ↑\\uparrow | Avg. Helpful ↑\\uparrow | Avg. All ↑\\uparrow | Train. Time ↓\\downarrow |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| base | base | online | rejection |\n| Qwen2.5-3B | 47.07 | 34.27 | 41.86 | 36.61 | 37.58 | 39.95 | – |\n| +GRPO | 61.75 | 68.78 | 70.73 | 71.64 | 70.38 | 68.23 | 2h54min |\n| +VAR | 63.30 | 66.29 | 70.07 | 69.32 | 68.56 | 67.25 | 42min |\n| Llama3.2-3B | 33.03 | 25.44 | 30.86 | 26.94 | 27.75 | 29.06 | – |\n| +SFT+GRPO | 56.34 | 59.98 | 62.32 | 62.72 | 61.67 | 60.34 | 3h8min |\n| +VAR | 57.97 | 60.23 | 64.92 | 62.92 | 62.69 | 61.51 | 37min |\n\nWe evaluate our offline VAR method against the online GRPO approach (Shao et al., [2024](#bib.bib28 \"DeepSeekMath: pushing the limits of mathematical reasoning in open language models\")) using the OffsetBias training set, with results measured on the HHA test sets (Table [4](#S4.T4 \"Table 4 ‣ Comparison with Online Methods ‣ 4.2 HHA Results ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\")). Despite being an offline method, VAR achieves comparable performance to GRPO on Qwen2.5-3B and even outperforms it on Llama3.2-3B (where GRPO requires SFT initialization for stable training). Notably, VAR trains approximately 5× faster per epoch than GRPO, demonstrating its efficiency while maintaining competitive performance with significantly fewer computational resources.\n\n### 4.3 Generative Benchmark\n\n#### Settings\n\nFollowing prior settings (Tunstall et al., [2023](#bib.bib38 \"Zephyr: direct distillation of lm alignment\"); Ethayarajh et al., [2024](#bib.bib31 \"Kto: model alignment as prospect theoretic optimization\")), we utilize UltraFeedback (Cui et al., [2023](#bib.bib39 \"UltraFeedback: boosting language models with high-quality feedback\")) as the training dataset. UltraFeedback is a large-scale preference dataset collected from diverse sources, where multiple LLMs generate four distinct responses for each prompt. The dataset comprises 64k prompts, resulting in 256k samples. Additionally, it includes GPT-4-evaluated scores for instruction-following, truthfulness, honesty, and helpfulness. For our experiments, we sampled 10k prompts, selecting the highest average-scored samples for training SFT, OURS, and ALoL, and using the highest-worst score pairs for training DPO. For training, we utilize Llama2-7B and Qwen2.5-7B as the base models. For comparison, we benchmark our method against ALoL and DPO. As for the reward model, we employ OffsetBiasRM for both ALoL and our method, with the same setting in HHA experiments.\n\n#### Implementation Details\n\nFor all experiments, we use 4×84\\times 8 A100-80GB GPUs, training with a learning rate of 5e-6 and the AdamW optimizer combined with a cosine learning rate scheduler for exactly two epochs. We evaluate the aligned models using the OpenCompass (Contributors, [2023](#bib.bib41 \"OpenCompass: a universal evaluation platform for foundation models\")) toolkit, with the following benchmarks: GSM8K (4-shot), MMLU (0-shot), HumanEval (0-shot), and BBH (3-shot chain-of-thought), following the default settings from OpenCompass. For GSM8K, MMLU, and BBH, we use exact match (EM) as the evaluation metric, while for HumanEval, we use pass@1.\n\n#### Generative Benchmark Results\n\nTable [3](#S4.F3 \"Figure 3 ‣ Generative Benchmark Results ‣ 4.3 Generative Benchmark ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") presents the results of different methods on Llama2-7B and Qwen2.5-7B models across four benchmarks: MMLU, GSM8k, HumanEval, and BBH. For Llama2-7B, our method consistently outperforms both DPO and ALoL across most benchmarks, achieving the highest average results. On Qwen2.5-7B, our method also demonstrates strong results, achieving the best performance on multiple benchmarks while maintaining competitive results on others, highlighting the robustness and effectiveness across various settings.\n\nTable 5: Benchmark comparison of different alignment methods on Llama2-7B and Qwen2.5-7B models. Results are shown for MMLU, GSM8K, HumanEval, and BBH, along with the average score across all benchmarks. Best results for each model are bolded.\n\n| Method | MMLU | GSM8k | HumanEval | BBH | Avg. ↑\\uparrow |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| EM ↑\\uparrow | EM ↑\\uparrow | pass@1 ↑\\uparrow | EM ↑\\uparrow |\n| Llama2-7B | Base | 37.46 | 1.90 | 3.05 | 12.77 | 13.79 |\n| DPO | 32.45 | 4.55 | 7.32 | 39.10 | 20.86 |\n| ALoL | 35.78 | 4.09 | 12.80 | 38.16 | 22.71 |\n| VAR | 38.57 | 6.67 | 14.02 | 37.56 | 24.20 |\n| Qwen2.5-7B | Base | 67.13 | 86.13 | 64.63 | 29.30 | 61.80 |\n| DPO | 68.64 | 74.53 | 33.54 | 53.06 | 57.44 |\n| ALoL | 68.62 | 64.97 | 54.88 | 61.14 | 62.40 |\n| VAR | 69.11 | 74.30 | 68.90 | 61.35 | 68.42 |\n\n![Refer to caption](2502.11026v3/figures/length.png) \n\nFigure 3: Distribution of output sequence lengths for aligned Llama3.1-8B on the HHA test set.\n\n  \n\nTable 6: Conversational benchmark results on AlpacaEval 2.0 and Arena-Hard 0.1.\n\n| Method | AlpacaEval 2.0 ↑\\uparrow | Arena-Hard 0.1 ↑\\uparrow |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| LC (%) | WR (%) | WR (%) |\n| Base | 4.01 | 3.73 | 8.4 |\n| DPO | 8.73 | 4.78 | 8.6 |\n| VAR | 8.26 | 4.29 | 10.8 |\n\nTo further assess general conversational ability, we also evaluate the models on AlpacaEval 2.0 and Arena-Hard 0.1. The results are presented in Table [6](#S4.T6 \"Table 6 ‣ Generative Benchmark Results ‣ 4.3 Generative Benchmark ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"). On the AlpacaEval 2.0 benchmark, DPO shows a slight advantage, achieving a 4.78% win rate (WR) and an 8.73% length-controlled (LC) win rate, compared to 4.29% and 8.26% for VAR, respectively. However, on the more challenging Arena-Hard 0.1 benchmark, our VAR method clearly outperforms DPO, scoring 10.8% to DPO’s 8.6%. This suggests that the two methods may have different strengths across various conversational benchmarks.\n\n### 4.4 Output Sequence Length Analysis\n\nWe calculate the average output sequence lengths for models aligned on Llama3.1-8B across the four subsets of HHA, as shown in Figure [3](#S4.F3 \"Figure 3 ‣ Generative Benchmark Results ‣ 4.3 Generative Benchmark ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"). Starting from the base models, DPO generates longer sequences than our method. When starting from SFT, our models maintain output sequence lengths similar to the SFT version, while DPO produces sequences approximately twice as long as ours and the SFT version. Longer sequences tend to achieve higher reward scores and GPT-based scores (Baheti et al., [2024](#bib.bib13 \"Leftover lunch: advantage-based offline reinforcement learning for language models\"); Ethayarajh et al., [2024](#bib.bib31 \"Kto: model alignment as prospect theoretic optimization\")). Despite this, our method outperforms DPO in most reward evaluations and winrate evaluations.\n\n### 4.5 Ablation Study\n\n \n\nTable 7: Ablation study of different batch sizes BB on Qwen2.5-7B model and πref\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}} sampled alternative (8∗).\n\n| BB | MMLU | GSM8k | HumanEval | BBH | Avg. ↑\\uparrow |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| EM ↑\\uparrow | EM ↑\\uparrow | pass@1 ↑\\uparrow | EM ↑\\uparrow |\n| 2 | 69.59 | 72.55 | 65.24 | 62.57 | 67.49 |\n| 4 | 69.09 | 75.44 | 68.29 | 60.32 | 68.28 |\n| 8 | 69.11 | 74.30 | 68.90 | 61.35 | 68.42 |\n| 8∗ | 67.83 | 75.97 | 65.85 | 63.66 | 68.32 |\n\nAs in Equation [9](#S3.E9 \"In 3.2 Batch-wise Partition Estimation ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"), we estimate Z​(𝒙i)Z({\\bm{x}}\\_{i}) with a micro batch, making batch size BB crucial for training. We conduct an ablation study using batch sizes 2, 4, and 8 under the settings in Section [4.3](#S4.SS3 \"4.3 Generative Benchmark ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"), with UltraFeedback as the training set. Table [7](#S4.T7 \"Table 7 ‣ 4.5 Ablation Study ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") shows the impact of different BB values on model performance. The model performs best at B=8B=8, but the improvement over B=4B=4 is just 0.14%, suggesting that a larger BB can slightly boost performance. Thus, we use B=8B=8 for all experiments. However, our method is also robust to batch-size changes, which gives satisfactory results even at B=2B=2, showing stability and suitability for resource-constrained situations.444We provide case study in Appendix [C](#A3 \"Appendix C Case Study ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"), from which we can observe our method effectively produce more comprehensive and helpful response with higher quality compared to the baseline methods.\n\nFurthermore, we compare our in-batch (offline) estimator to an alternative strategy, πref\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}} sampled (B=8B=8), which estimates Z^​(x)\\hat{Z}(x) using dedicated candidates pre-sampled from πref\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}} for each prompt. As shown in the last row of Table [7](#S4.T7 \"Table 7 ‣ 4.5 Ablation Study ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"), this alternative approach is not only significantly more costly (requiring a separate, large-scale pre-sampling process) but also results in slightly lower performance (68.32 Avg. vs. 68.42 Avg.). This result validates our choice of the more efficient and effective in-batch estimation strategy.\n\n### 4.6 Analyses of Z​(x)Z(x) Estimation\n\n![Refer to caption](2502.11026v3/figures/z_variance_offline.png) \n\n(a) Offline (In-Batch) Estimation\n\n![Refer to caption](2502.11026v3/figures/z_variance_online_sample.png) \n\n(b) Online Sample Estimation\n\nFigure 4: The variance of the partition function estimate Z^​(x)\\hat{Z}(x) versus the micro-batch size BB.\n\n \n\nThe stability of our VAR method depends heavily on getting a good estimate for the partition function Z​(x)Z(x). Our approach uses an efficient Monte Carlo estimation based on the samples already available in the training micro-batch (as described in Equation [9](#S3.E9 \"In 3.2 Batch-wise Partition Estimation ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") and Algorithm [1](#algorithm1 \"In 3.2 Batch-wise Partition Estimation ‣ 3 Methodology ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\")). A fair question is how reliable this estimate is, and specifically, how the micro-batch size BB affects its variance.\n\nTo investigate this, we ran an analysis, shown in Figure [4](#S4.F4 \"Figure 4 ‣ 4.6 Analyses of 𝑍⁢(𝑥) Estimation ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"). We compare the variance of Z^​(x)\\hat{Z}(x) under two different estimation strategies: (1) Offline (In-Batch) Estimation (Figure [4](#S4.F4 \"Figure 4 ‣ 4.6 Analyses of 𝑍⁢(𝑥) Estimation ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") (a)): This is the method we use in this work; it leverages the BB samples already in the micro-batch to calculate Z^​(xi)\\hat{Z}(x\\_{i}) for each xix\\_{i} in that batch. The plot clearly shows that the variance drops sharply as BB increases from 22 to 88. This confirms that even a modest batch size (like B=8B=8, which we used in our experiments ) provides a significantly more stable estimate than a very small one. (2) Online Sample Estimation (Figure [4](#S4.F4 \"Figure 4 ‣ 4.6 Analyses of 𝑍⁢(𝑥) Estimation ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\") (b)): For comparison, we simulated an “online” approach. Here, for each xix\\_{i}, we would need to actively sample BB new responses from the reference policy πref\\pi\\_{\\text{ref}} to compute Z^​(xi)\\hat{Z}(x\\_{i}).\n\nThis analysis confirms our design choice. The online method is not only computationally expensive (requiring BB extra sampling steps per instance) but also shows a higher and less consistent variance at small batch sizes. Our in-batch (offline) method is significantly more efficient and yields a stable, low-variance estimate as the batch size increases.\n\n### 4.7 Computational Overhead Analysis\n\n \n\nTable 8: Computational profile comparison for a single training epoch (Llama3.2-3B, B=8B=8, 4×\\timesA100-80GB).\n\n| Method | Wall Clock | Throughput | Peak GPU |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Time/Epoch ↓\\downarrow | Tokens/s ↑\\uparrow | Mem./GPU ↓\\downarrow |\n| SFT | ∼\\sim28min | ∼\\sim2945 | ∼\\sim31 GB |\n| DPO | ∼\\sim32min | ∼\\sim2577 | ∼\\sim39 GB |\n| VAR | ∼\\sim37min | ∼\\sim2228 | ∼\\sim38 GB |\n\nOur method is structured to avoid adding significant overhead to the main training loop. We achieve this by integrating the costliest parts of the Z^​(x)\\hat{Z}(x) estimation into the data preprocessing step: (1) Preparation: Before the main training loop starts, we pre-shuffle the training data and split it into the exact micro-batches (e.g., B=8B=8) that will be used for training. (2) Reward Calculation: We then calculate the reward r​(xi,yj)r(x\\_{i},y\\_{j}) for each in-batch pair and store these values on disk.\n\nTherefore, during training, we only need to perform one major extra step compared to standard SFT: a forward pass through the reference model (πref\\pi\\_{\\mathrm{ref}}) to obtain the logits necessary to compute Z^​(x)\\hat{Z}(x) (using the pre-calculated rewards). However, the most time-consuming part of training LLMs is the backward pass (gradient computation). Since our training loop does not involve running the backward pass on the reference model (πref\\pi\\_{\\mathrm{ref}} is frozen), the minimal extra cost incurred by the single forward pass is negligible when amortized over the entire training process.\n\nWe provide a direct comparison of SFT, DPO, and VAR in Table [8](#S4.T8 \"Table 8 ‣ 4.7 Computational Overhead Analysis ‣ 4 Experiments ‣ RLHF in an SFT Way: From Optimal Solution to Reward-Weighted Alignment\"), run under identical settings (Llama3.2-3B, 4×\\timesA100-80GB GPUs, B=8B=8). The results confirm our approach is highly efficient. As shown in the table, the wall clock time per epoch for VAR (37min) is close to SFT (28min) and DPO (32min). This minimal time difference is reflected in a slight reduction in throughput. For peak memory, VAR is comparable to DPO, as both must load the πref\\pi\\_{\\mathrm{ref}}.\n\n## 5 Related Work\n\nAligning LLMs with human preferences has evolved from studies on RLHF, aiming to achieve human-aligned outcomes (Stiennon et al., [2020](#bib.bib36 \"Learning to summarize with human feedback\"); Ouyang et al., [2022](#bib.bib7 \"Training language models to follow instructions with human feedback\"); Bai et al., [2022](#bib.bib15 \"Training a helpful and harmless assistant with reinforcement learning from human feedback\"); Lee et al., [2023](#bib.bib42 \"Rlaif: scaling reinforcement learning from human feedback with ai feedback\")). The RLHF process typically begins with SFT, followed by further fine-tuning to maximize expected reward scores. This requires the construction of a reward model (Bradley and Terry, [1952](#bib.bib57 \"Rank analysis of incomplete block designs: i. the method of paired comparisons\"); Li et al., [2025c](#bib.bib77 \"APLOT: robust reward modeling via adaptive preference learning with optimal transport\"); [a](#bib.bib88 \"Eliminating inductive bias in reward models with information-theoretic guidance\")) based on the Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE) of the BT model to provide such reward scores. This fine-tuning process is referred to as RLHF, with the PPO algorithm being the most widely applied (Schulman et al., [2017](#bib.bib27 \"Proximal policy optimization algorithms\")). A series of works focus on self-training, where the workflow involves sampling online data from the model and training it using a two-player min-max game between two policies (Rosset et al., [2024](#bib.bib33 \"Direct nash optimization: teaching language models to self-improve with general preferences\"); Swamy et al., [2024](#bib.bib34 \"A minimaximalist approach to reinforcement learning from human feedback\"); Chen et al., [2024](#bib.bib35 \"Self-play fine-tuning converts weak language models to strong language models\")). However, the use of online data in the learning process presents significant challenges, as it requires substantial computational resources and limits training efficiency. To address these challenges, researchers have shifted their focus to offline preference alignment learning algorithms. These methods operate in a single stage and directly optimize a designed loss function to achieve optimal preference alignment based on pairwise datasets (Zhao et al., [2023](#bib.bib29 \"SLiC-hf: sequence likelihood calibration with human feedback\"); Rafailov et al., [2024](#bib.bib23 \"Direct preference optimization: your language model is secretly a reward model\"); Azar et al., [2024](#bib.bib30 \"A general theoretical paradigm to understand learning from human preferences\"); Ethayarajh et al., [2024](#bib.bib31 \"Kto: model alignment as prospect theoretic optimization\"); Xu et al., [2024](#bib.bib32 \"Contrastive preference optimization: pushing the boundaries of llm performance in machine translation\")). However, standard offline methods like DPO often rely on a fixed reference model, which can lead to optimization instability. To mitigate this, recent alternatives have proposed eliminating the reference-policy mismatch via reference-free objectives (Meng et al., [2024](#bib.bib80 \"Simpo: simple preference optimization with a reference-free reward\")) or minimizing the divergence by learning a better reference model (Gorbatovski et al., [2024](#bib.bib81 \"Learn your reference model for real good alignment\")). Separately, to alleviate the resource-intensive nature of training, Remax (Li et al., [2024b](#bib.bib37 \"ReMax: a simple, effective, and efficient reinforcement learning method for aligning large language models\")) introduces a variance reduction method for LLMs. Most closely related to our work is ALoL (Baheti et al., [2024](#bib.bib13 \"Leftover lunch: advantage-based offline reinforcement learning for language models\")), which formulates the reinforcement learning process at the sequence level and derives its advantage-based offline objective. This sequence-level perspective is further supported by recent theoretical analysis linking SFT generalization to reward rectification (Wu et al., [2025](#bib.bib82 \"On the generalization of sft: a reinforcement learning perspective with reward rectification\")), reinforcing the motivation for formulating RLHF within a supervised framework. However, unlike ALoL that relies on heuristic clipping, or methods like SimPO that discard the reference model, we formulate our approach by directly approximating the optimal solution of RLHF via variational inference, thereby achieving a more precise and stable solution.\n\n## 6 Conclusion\n\nThis paper proposed a reward-driven variational alignment framework to address the limitations of existing RLHF methods, such as instability from negative weights and suboptimal performance due to clipping. By reformulating RLHF as a variational problem over positive measures, our approach ensures a stable optimization landscape and derives a reward-driven weighted SFT loss through KL divergence minimization. The introduction of an efficient in-batch normalization technique further enables scalable and practical implementation. Experimental results demonstrate improved alignment performance and training stability, offering a effective solution for preference alignment in LLM.\n\n## Impact Statement\n\nThe Variational Alignment with Re-weighting (VAR) method has a significant impact on LLM alignment, providing an efficient and stable alternative to complex RLHF pipelines. While our focus is on improving alignment performance and training stability, we recognize the broader societal implications, including the risks of bias amplification, misuse of generative capabilities, and ethical concerns surrounding the automation of human-like decision-making. We emphasize the need for ongoing research to address these challenges and ensure responsible deployment of RLHF advancements.\n\n## Acknowledgment\n\nThis work was supported by the Guangxi Key R&D Project (No. AB24010167), Guangxi Science and Technology Program under Grant No. FN2504240022, the Project (No. 20232ABC03A25), Shenzhen Longgang District Science and Technology Innovation Special Fund (No. LGKCYLWS2023018), Futian Healthcare Research Project (No.FTWS002), and C