{i=1}^{n}\\alpha\\_{i}\\log\\pi\\_{\\theta}(y\\_{i}|x), | (17) |\n\nand ∑αi=1\\sum\\alpha\\_{i}=1. By using the Lagrange’s method, construct (for simplicity, write zi=πθ​(yi|x)z\\_{i}=\\pi\\_{\\theta}(y\\_{i}|x))\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| F​(z1,z2,…,zn,β)=∑i=1nαi​log⁡zi−β​(∑i=1nzi−1),F(z\\_{1},z\\_{2},...,z\\_{n},\\beta)=\\sum\\_{i=1}^{n}\\alpha\\_{i}\\log z\\_{i}-\\beta(\\sum\\_{i=1}^{n}z\\_{i}-1), | (18) |\n\nand the partial derivatives are\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| ∂F∂zi=αizi−β,∂F∂β=−(∑i=1nzi−1).\\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial z\\_{i}}=\\frac{\\alpha\\_{i}}{z\\_{i}}-\\beta,\\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial\\beta}=-(\\sum\\_{i=1}^{n}z\\_{i}-1). | (19) |\n\nHence we can see that the optimal solution of the A-LoL loss is: (BY solving the partial derivatives the optimal solution must have the same distribution as αi\\alpha\\_{i})\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| π∗​(yi|x)/π∗​({y1,…,yn}|x)=R​(x,yi)⋅clip​(r​(θ1,r​e​f),1−ϵ,1+ϵ)−β∑j=1n(R​(x,yj)⋅clip​(r​(θ1,r​e​f),1−ϵ,1+ϵ)−β).\\pi^{\\*}(y\\_{i}|x)/\\pi^{\\*}(\\{y\\_{1},...,y\\_{n}\\}|x)=\\frac{R(x,y\\_{i})\\cdot\\text{clip}(r(\\theta\\_{1},ref),1-\\epsilon,1+\\epsilon)-\\beta}{\\sum\\_{j=1}^{n}(R(x,y\\_{j})\\cdot\\text{clip}(r(\\theta\\_{1},ref),1-\\epsilon,1+\\epsilon)-\\beta)}. | (20) |\n\nSo we can see that for close rewards responses, this optimal solution will not distinguish their distributions. For example, if we have two responses y1,y2y\\_{1},y\\_{2} with R1,R2R\\_{1},R\\_{2} as their rewards, then the A-LoL method will give R1R1+R2\\frac{R\\_{1}}{R\\_{1}+R\\_{2}} and R2R1+R2\\frac{R\\_{2}}{R\\_{1}+R\\_{2}} as the optimal solution and could be closed to 1/21/2 if R1/R2R\\_{1}/R\\_{2} is closed to 11 (e.g. R1=100,R2=99R\\_{1}=100,R\\_{2}=99). However, for our method, it will distinguished by exp⁡(R1−R2)\\exp(R\\_{1}-R\\_{2}), i.e. for R1=100,R2=99R\\_{1}=100,R\\_{2}=99, our method gives us ee+1\\frac{e}{e+1} and 1e+1\\frac{1}{e+1}, which seems better.\n\n### A.2 Loss Bound Analysis\n\n#### Lower Bound of Positive Weig