XML maintain a [list of packages that need conversion](https://github.com/brucemiller/LaTeXML/wiki/Porting-LaTeX-packages-for-LaTeXML), and welcome [developer contributions](https://github.com/brucemiller/LaTeXML/issues).\n\nBETA\n\n "},{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1","title":"Is DPO Superior to PPO for LLM Alignment? A Comprehensive Study","content":"This paper concentrates on RLHF methods, which can be broadly categorized into reward-based and reward-free approaches. Reward-based methods entail training a","score":0.9998795,"raw_content":"# Is DPO Superior to PPO for LLM Alignment? A Comprehensive Study\n\n###### Abstract\n\nReinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) is currently the most widely used method to align large language models (LLMs) with human preferences.\nExisting RLHF methods can be roughly categorized as either reward-based or reward-free.\nNovel applications such as ChatGPT and Claude leverage reward-based methods that first learn a reward model and apply actor-critic algorithms, such as Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO).\nHowever, in academic benchmarks, the state-of-the-art results are often achieved via reward-free methods, such as Direct Preference Optimization (DPO).\nIs DPO truly superior to PPO?\n\nWhy does PPO perform poorly on these benchmarks?\nIn this paper, we first conduct both theoretical and empirical studies on the algorithmic properties of DPO and show that DPO may have fundamental limitations.\nMoreover, we also comprehensively examine PPO and reveal the key factors for the best performances of PPO in fine-tuning LLMs. Finally, we benchmark DPO and PPO across various a collection of RLHF testbeds, ranging from dialogue to code generation. Experiment results demonstrate that PPO is able to surpass other alignment methods in all cases and achieve state-of-the-art results in challenging code competitions.\n\n## 1 Introduction\n\nLarge Language Models (LLMs) derive their extensive language patterns and knowledge through pre-training on substantial textual datasets (Brown et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib7); OpenAI, [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib30); Touvron et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib51); Chowdhery et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib10); Anil et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib3)). To leverage the formidable capabilities of LLMs in practical applications, a growing amount of research has underscored the importance of aligning these models with human preferences (Agrawal et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib1); Kadavath et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib19); Shi et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib45); Liang et al., [2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib25); Sheng et al., [2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib44)). Various methods have been developed for fine-tuning LLMs, with popular approaches including Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) (Peng et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib32)) and Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) (Ziegler et al., [2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib59); Stiennon et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib48); Ouyang et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib31)). Typically, fine-tuning involves two phases: SFT to establish a base model, followed by RLHF for enhanced performance. SFT involves imitating high-quality demonstration data, while RLHF refines LLMs through preference feedback.\n\nWithin RLHF, two prominent approaches are reward-based and reward-free methods. Reward-based methods, pioneered by OpenAI (Ouyang et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib31); Ziegler et al., [2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib59); Stiennon et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib48)), construct a reward model using preference data and then employ actor-critic algorithms like Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) to optimize the reward signal. In contrast, reward-free methods, including Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) (Rafailov et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib34)), RRHF (Yuan et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib56)), and PRO (Song et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib47)), eliminate the explicit use of a reward function. DPO, a representative reward-free method, expresses the reward function in a logarithmic form of the policy and focuses solely on policy optimization.\n\nNotably, the most successful applications like ChatGPT (OpenAI, [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib29)) and Claude (Antropic, [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib4)) are produced by the reward-based RLHF method PPO, while strong performances in academic benchmarks often result from the reward-free RLHF method DPO (Rafailov et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib34); MistralAI, [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib27)). This discrepancy raises two fundamental questions: 1) Is DPO truly superior to PPO in the RLHF domain? and 2) Can the performance of PPO be substantially improved in common RLHF benchmarks? In this paper, we delve into these questions. Through theoretical and empirical analysis, we uncover the fundamental limitations of DPO and explore critical factors that enhance the practical performance of PPO in RLHF.\n\nFirst, our theoretical examination reveals that\nDPO might find biased solutions that exploit out-of-distribution responses.\nEmpirically, we demonstrate that the performance of DPO is significantly affected by the distribution shift between the model outputs and the preference dataset.\nSecond, we perform ablation studies on the algorithmic components of PPO and discover a collection of critical factors for PPO’s best RLHF performances, including advantage normalization, large batch size, and exponential moving average update for the reference model. Finally, we validate our findings through extensive experiments, including dialogue generation tasks and more challenging code generation tasks. These experiments feature diverse feedback types and difficulty levels.\nThe results indicate that PPO consistently outperforms DPO across all experiments.\nParticularly, in the most challenging code competition tasks, PPO achieves state-of-the-art results. Specifically, on the CodeContest dataset (Li et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib24)), our PPO model with 34B parameters outperforms AlphaCode-41B (Li et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib24)), exhibiting a 10@1k improvement from 16.4% to 22.4%.\n\n## 2 Related Work\n\nLarge language models (LLMs) trained on large datasets acquire surprising capabilities (Brown et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib7); OpenAI, [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib30); Touvron et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib51); Chowdhery et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib10); Anil et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib3); Kaplan et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib20); Brown et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib7)).\nTo leverage these capabilities to real applications, pre-trained LLM is further fine-tuned on specific tasks (Radford et al., [2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib33); Chung et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib12); Tay et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib50)). Through fine-tuning with popular approaches such as SFT and RLHF, LLMs demonstrate impressive performance on established benchmarks (Touvron et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib51); OpenAI, [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib30)), aligning further with human preferences and societal well-being (Russell & Norvig, [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib39); Russell, [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib38)).\n\nThis paper concentrates on RLHF methods, which can be broadly categorized into reward-based and reward-free approaches.\nReward-based methods entail training a reward model on preference data in an initial phase (Gao et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib16); Ziegler et al., [2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib59); Stiennon et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib48); Ouyang et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib31)). Subsequently, this learned reward model is utilized to provide a reward signal for online Reinforcement Learning (RL) algorithms such as PPO (Schulman et al., [2017](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib42)).\nThere exist previous works that have studied these methods through hyper-parameter tuning and analyzed the effects of the quality reward model quality (Zheng et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib58); Casper et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib8)).\nIn contrast, reward-free methods offer a simpler training procedure by directly training LLMs on preference data or ranking data to distill human preference (Yuan et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib56); Liu et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib26); Touvron et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib51); Rafailov et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib34); Song et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib47); Dong et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib14)).\nAmong these reward-free methods, DPO (Rafailov et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib34)) has demonstrated strong performances and become popular in the community (MistralAI, [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib27); Chen et al., [2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib9); Yuan et al., [2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib55)).\nThis paper examines representatives from both categories, specifically PPO and DPO. We analyze the limitations of DPO theoretically and empirically and explore the key factors for PPO training.\n\nConcurrent efforts have been undertaken to avoid reward model overoptimization (Ramé et al., [2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib37)), facilitate alignment data generation (Lee et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib22); Yang et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib52)), and implement resource-efficient RLHF systems (Yao et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib53); Santacroce et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib40)).\nThese works complement our study and can be seamlessly integrated into our implementation.\nPrevious works have explored the implementation details of PPO for LLMs (Zheng et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib58); Ramamurthy et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib36)). Our paper extends its investigations with additional RLHF techniques, optimizing PPO performance to surpass its reward-free counterpart, DPO. This is an aspect not previously reported in the literature.\nOur work is also closely related to studies on algorithm implementation in the RL community (Engstrom et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib15); Andrychowicz et al., [2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib2); Yu et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2404.10719v1#bib.bib54)). However, our findings provide further insights into fine-tuning LLMs with a model size of up to 34B parameters.\n\n## 3 Preliminary\n\nLanguage Model. We consider an LLM as a policy πθ⁢(𝐲∣𝐱)subscript𝜋𝜃conditional𝐲𝐱\\pi\\_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{y}\\mid\\mathbf{x})italic\\_π start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_θ end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold\\_y ∣ bold\\_x ) par